                <redfort class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3"><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Fort"><img class="image" src="./redfort.jpg"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"><u><b>Redfort </b></u><br>Red Fort, also called Lal Qalʿah, also spelled Lal Kila or Lal Qila, Mughal fort in Old Delhi, India. It was built by Shah Jahān in the mid-17th century.It is a monument of national significance; every year on India's Independence Day (15 August), the Prime Minister of India hoists the country's flag at the Red Fort and delivers a nationally broadcast speech from its ramparts. </button></a> </div></redfort>
                <charminar class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3"><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charminar"><img class="image" src="./Charminar.jpg"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"> <u><b>Charminar</b></u> <br>The Charminar constructed in 1591, is a monument located in Hyderabad, Telangana, India. The landmark has become known globally as a symbol of Hyderabad and is listed among the most recognised structures in India. Charminar, the Mosque of the four minarets, was built by Muhammad Quli Qutb Shah.</button></a></div></charminar>
                <qutub class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3"><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qutb_Minar"><img class="image" src="./qutub.jpg"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"> <u><b>Qutub Minar</b></u> <br>Qutab Minar is a soaring, 73 m-high tower of victory, built in 1193 by Qutab-ud-din Aibak immediately after the defeat of Delhi's last Hindu kingdom.Delhi Qutub Minar boasts of being one of the tallest minarets in the world as the height of Qutub Minar is 72.5 meters. Built in 1192 by Qutab-ud-din Aibak.</button></a></div></qutub>
                <ajanta class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3"><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellora_Caves"><img class="image" src="./ajanta.jpg"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"><u><b> Ajanta-Ellora caves </b></u><br>Ellora is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in the Aurangabad district of Maharashtra, India.The Ajanta Caves constitute ancient monasteries and worship-halls of different Buddhist traditions carved into a 75-metre (246 ft) wall of rock.</button></a></div></ajanta>
                <hawa class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3"><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawa_Mahal"><img class="image" src="./hawamahal.png"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"> <u><b>Hawa Mahal </b></u><br>The Hawa Mahal is a palace in the city of Jaipur, India. Built from red and pink sandstone, it is on the edge of the City Palace, Jaipur, and extends to the Zenana, or women's chambers.Hawa Mahal was built by Kachhwaha Rajput ruler Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh in the year 1799.</button></a></div></hawa>
                <mysore class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3"><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysore_Palace"><img class="image" src="./mysore.jpg"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"><u><b> Mysore Palace </b></u><br>The Mysore Palace, also known as Amba Vilas Palace, is a historical palace and a royal residence (house). It is located in Mysore, Karnataka.Mysore Palace is one of the most famous tourist attractions in India, after the Taj Mahal, with more than six million annual visitors.</button></a></div></mysore>
                <victoria class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4  mb-3" ><div class="bg-white shadow b p-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria_Memorial,_Kolkata"><img class="image" src="./victoria.jpg"><br><button class="btn btn-group-sm"> <u><b>Victoria Mahal </b></u><br>The Victoria Memorial is a large marble building in Central Kolkata, which was built between 1906 and 1921. It is dedicated to the memory of Queen Victoria, Empress of India from 1876 to 1901. It is now a museum under the auspices of the Ministry of Culture, and is the largest monument in the world which is dedicated to a royal. </button></a></div></victoria>
